6 |archive-date=October 4, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  Prior to that, he was the Executive in Charge of Production for [[Electronic Arts]], overseeing [[Ultima Online]].<ref>[https://www.mobygames.com/developer/sheet/view/developerId,26529/ \"Jeffrey Anderson Video Games Credits\"] Retrieved March 27, 2020</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nJeffrey Anderson received an undergraduate degree from the [[University of Illinois]] where he was one in the top 3% of his graduating class.<ref>[https://digital.library.illinois.edu/items/af312ba0-13c4-0134-1d5f-0050569601ca-9#?c=0&m=0&s=0&cv=0&r=0&xywh=-1110%2C218%2C9092%2C3449 \"U. of I. Bronze Tablet 1989\"] Retrieved March 27, 2020</ref> He also has a [[Juris Doctor|JD]] from the [[University of Chicago]] where he served on the [[University of Chicago Law Review]].<ref>https://lawreview.uchicago.edu/sites/lawreview.uchicago.edu/files/uploads/About/Mastheads/v59.pdf</ref> After graduating, he went to work as an attorney at the law firm of Holleb & Coff in [[Chicago, Illinois]]. Feeling that the legal profession was not for him, he joined with Thomas Ptak and others to start [[Mission Studios]] (which was later sold to [[Take-Two]]). After that, he moved to [[Los Angeles]] and joined [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]'s consumer products division where he worked on various initiatives from [[Star Trek]] licensing to the [[Bubba Gump Shrimp Company]]. In 1998, [[Electronic Arts]] recruited him to join its [[Austin, Texas]] studio to oversee the [[Ultima Online]] franchise along with [[Raph Koster]] and [[Richard Garriott]]. Then, in 2001, [[Turbine Inc]] recruited him to be its President and CEO. The company had a software development agreement with [[Microsoft]] at the time to develop [[Asheron's Call 2]], but wanted to expand the business and become the largest independent [[MMORPG]] company in the world. Anderson successfully raised capital from [[Highland Capital Partners]] and [[Polaris Venture Partners]], and secured the rights to develop two new [[MMORPG]] games known as [[Dungeons & Dragons Online]] and [[The Lord of the Rings Online]]. After leaving Turbine in 2008 (which was subsequently sold to [[Warner Brothers]]<ref>http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/entertainmentnewsbuzz/2010/04/warner-bros-acquires-turbine.html</ref>), he founded [[Quick Hit]]. This new online gaming studio developed the world's first free-to-play [[National Football League]]-licensed online football game.<ref>https://venturebeat.com/2010/06/10/quick-hit-scores-nfl-license-for-online-football-games/</ref> The company raised capital from [[New Enterprise Associates]] before it was sold to Majesco in 2011. Two years after the sale, Anderson joined the [[Game Show Network]] as its CSO.\n\n==Awards==\n* ''[[Boston Globe]] 100 - Top Innovators in Massachusetts' <ref>http://archive.boston.com/business/technology/innoeco/2011/05/globe_100_ceo_roundtable_the_e.html</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anderson, Jeffrey}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American video game designers]]\n[[Category:American game designers]]\n[[Category:University of Illinois alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:American technology chief executives]]\n", "name_user": "Chusetts", "label": "safe", "comment": "Deleted an link that was redirected to a different Jeffrey Anderson on Bloomberg; cleaned up link formats", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeffrey_Anderson_(game_designer)"}
{"title_page": "Shawn Mennenga", "text_new": "{{short description|American football coach}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date = April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox NFL biography|name=Shawn Mennenga|image=|image_size=|alt=|caption=|current_team=Green Bay Packers|position=Special Teams  Coordinator|birth_date={{birth date and age|1971|1|8}}|birth_place=[[Melbourne, Iowa]]|death_date=|death_place=|high_school=[[Strongsville High School|Strongsville (OH)]]|college=[[University of Missouri]]|pastcoaching=* [[Southwest Baptist Bearcats football|Southwest Baptist University]] (1994)<br>Graduate Assistant \n* Southwest Baptist University (1995\u20131996)<br>Secondary Coach\n* [[Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football|Western Kentucky]] (1997)<br>Outside Linebackers Coach \n* [[Hutchinson Community College]] (1998-2000)<br> Defensive Coordinator  \n* [[Culver-Stockton College]] (2001)<br> Defensive Coordinator \n* Culver-Stockton College (2002\u20132004)<br> Head Coach \n* [[Fort Hays State University]] (2005-2008)<br> Defensive Coordinator \n* [[South Dakota State Jackrabbits football|Dough Dakota State University]] (2009\u20132010)<br> Linebackers Coach \n* [[Cleveland Browns]] ({{nfly|2011}}\u2013{{nfly|2017}})<br> Assistant Special Teams Coach \n* [[Vanderbilt Commodores football|Vanderbilt]] (2018)<br> Special Teams Coordinator \n* [[Green Bay Packers]]({{nfly|2019}}\u2013present)<br> Special Teams Coordinator}}\n\n'''Shawn Mennenga'''(born January 8, 1971) is an [[American football]] coach in the [[National Football League]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.profootballarchives.com/coach/menn00300coach.html|title=Shawn Mennenga - Pro Football Archives|website=www.profootballarchives.com|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> He has been the special teams coordinator for the [[Green Bay Packers]] <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.packers.com/team/coaches-roster/shawn-mennenga?campaign=sf:fanshare:facebook|title=Packers.com, the official website of the Green Bay Packers|website=www.packers.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.acmepackingcompany.com/2020/1/22/21076972/cheese-curds-packers-special-teams-improved-but-are-still-bad|title=Wednesday Cheese Curds: Packers special teams improved, but are still bad|last=Burke|first=Kris|date=2020-01-22|website=Acme Packing Company|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/sports/college/vanderbilt/2019/01/31/green-bay-packers-matt-lafleur-vanderbilt-coach-shawn-mennenga-titans/2733564002/|title=Reports: Matt LaFleur hires Vanderbilt's Shawn Mennenga for Green Bay Packers staff|last=Sparks|first=Adam|website=The Tennessean|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/sports/nfl/packers-special-teams-pass-first-test-under-new-coordinator-shawn-mennenga/ar-AAGWXrL|title=Packers special teams pass first test under new coordinator Shawn Mennenga|website=www.msn.com|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/blog/green-bay-packers/post/_/id/46785/shawn-mennenga-brings-the-dave-toub-approach-to-packers-special-teams|title=Shawn Mennenga brings the Dave Toub approach to Packers' special teams|date=2019-01-31|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> since [[2019 Green Bay Packers season|2019]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2019/01/31/report-packers-hire-shawn-mennenga-as-st-coach/|title=Report: Packers hire Shawn Mennenga as ST coach|last=Alper|first=Josh|date=2019-01-31|website=ProFootballTalk|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesrepublican.com/sports/local-sports/2019/03/from-small-town-iowa-to-the-nfl/|title=From small-town Iowa to the NFL|website=timesrepublican.com/|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> After beginning his NFL coaching career with the [[Cleveland Browns]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawgsbynature.com/2013/1/30/3933210/shawn-mennenga-stays-with-browns-as-special-teams-assistant|title=Shawn Mennenga Stays With Browns as ST Assistant|last=Pokorny|first=Chris|date=2013-01-30|website=Dawgs By Nature|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> in [[2011 Cleveland Browns season|2011]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cleveland.com/browns/2011/02/cleveland_browns_complete_thei.html|title=Cleveland Browns complete their first coaching staff under Pat Shurmur|last=Cabot|first=Mary Kay|last2=clevel|date=2011-02-15|website=cleveland|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11|last3=.com}}</ref> under [[Pat Shurmur]] after years of college coaching experience. During 2018 Shawn became the special teams coordinator for [[Vanderbilt Commodores football|Vanderbilt]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vanderbilthustler.com/16762/featured/derek-mason-seeking-revamped-special-teams-look-under-shawn-mennenga/|title=Derek Mason seeking revamped special teams look under Shawn Mennenga|last=Klein|first=Cutler|website=The Vanderbilt Hustler|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fanbuzz.com/college-football/sec/vanderbilt-shawn-menneng-special-teams/|title=SEC program steals away NFL coach with latest reported hire|last=Nardone|first=Joseph|date=2018-01-28|website=FanBuzz - Sports News - NFL {{!}} NCAA {{!}} NBA {{!}}  WWE|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> before ultimately returning to the NFL.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.12up.com/posts/6285338-report-packers-hire-shawn-mennenga-as-new-special-teams-coach|title=REPORT: Packers Hire Shawn Mennenga as New Special Teams Coach|date=2019-01-31|website=12up.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n== Family ==\nMennenga and his wife, Christie, have a son, Garrett, and a daughter, Ashley.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Cleveland Browns coaches]]\n[[Category:Green Bay Packers coaches]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Iowa]]\n[[Category:Vanderbilt Commodores coaches]]\n[[Category:Vanderbilt Commodores 