{"title_page": "Shota Arveladze", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name                 = Shota Arveladze<br /><small>\u10e8\u10dd\u10d7\u10d0 \u10d0\u10e0\u10d5\u10d4\u10da\u10d0\u10eb\u10d4</small>\n| image                = Shota Arveladze in FC Pakhtakor.jpg\n| caption              = Arveladze in 2019\n| image_size           = 235px\n| fullname             = Shota Arveladze\n| birth_date           = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1973|2|22}}\n| birth_place          = [[Tbilisi]], Soviet Union\n| height               = 1.82m\n| position             = [[Forward (association football)|Striker]]\n| currentclub          = [[Pakhtakor Tashkent FK|Pakhtakor Tashkent]] (manager)\n| youthyears1          = 1987\u20131990\n| youthclubs1          = [[FC Dinamo Tbilisi|Dinamo Tbilisi]]\n| years1               = 1990\u20131991\n| clubs1               = [[FC Dinamo Tbilisi|Martve Tbilisi]]\n| caps1                = 30\n| goals1               = 33\n| years2               = 1991\u20131994\n| clubs2               = [[FC Dinamo Tbilisi|Dinamo Tbilisi]]\n| caps2                = 67\n| goals2               = 51\n| years3               = 1993\u20131994\n| clubs3               = \u2192 [[Trabzonspor]] ''(loan)''\n| caps3                = 18\n| goals3               = 15\n| years4               = 1995\u20131997\n| clubs4               = [[Trabzonspor]]\n| caps4                = 76\n| goals4               = 46\n| years5               = 1997\u20132001\n| clubs5               = [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]]\n| caps5                = 96\n| goals5               = 55\n| years6               = 2001\u20132005\n| clubs6               = [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]\n| caps6                = 95\n| goals6               = 44\n| years7               = 2005\u20132007\n| clubs7               = [[AZ (football club)|AZ]]\n| caps7                = 60\n| goals7               = 36\n| years8               = 2007\u20132008\n| clubs8               = [[Levante UD|Levante]]\n| caps8                = 4\n| goals8               = 0\n| totalcaps            = 426\n| totalgoals           = 258\n| nationalyears1       = 1992\u20132007\n| nationalteam1        = [[Georgia national football team|Georgia]]\n| nationalcaps1        = 61\n| nationalgoals1       = 26\n| manageryears1        = 2008\u20132010 \n| managerclubs1        = [[AZ (football club)|AZ]] (assistant)\n| manageryears2        = 2010\u20132012\n| managerclubs2        = [[Kayserispor]]\n| manageryears3        = 2012\u20132015\n| managerclubs3        = [[Kas\u0131mpa\u015fa Spor Kul\u00fcb\u00fc|Kas\u0131mpa\u015fa]]\n| manageryears4        = 2015\n| managerclubs4        = [[Trabzonspor]]\n| manageryears5        = 2016\u20132017\n| managerclubs5        = [[Maccabi Tel Aviv F.C.|Maccabi Tel Aviv]]\n| manageryears6        = 2017\u2013                       \n| managerclubs6        = [[Pakhtakor Tashkent FK|Pakhtakor Tashkent]]\n}}\n\n'''Shota Arveladze''' ({{lang-ka|\u10e8\u10dd\u10d7\u10d0 \u10d0\u10e0\u10d5\u10d4\u10da\u10d0\u10eb\u10d4}}; born 22 February 1973) is a [[Georgia (country)|Georgian]] former professional [[Association football|footballer]] and current [[Manager (association football)|manager]] of [[Pakhtakor Tashkent FK|Pakhtakor Tashkent]].\n\nArveladze played at [[FC Dinamo Tbilisi|Dinamo Tbilisi]], [[Trabzonspor]], [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]], [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], [[AZ (football club)|AZ]] and [[Levante UD|Levante]].\n\nHe is [[Georgia (country)|Georgia\u2019s]] all-time top scorer with 291 goals in his 410 league games for his clubs and 26 goals in his 61 games for the [[Georgia national football team|national team]].<ref name=\"Bibileishvili\">Bibileishvili, Tiko (9 June 2008) [http://www.geotimes.ge/index.php?m=home&newsid=11166 Arveladze Quits Football] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080813060147/http://www.geotimes.ge/index.php?m=home&newsid=11166 |date=13 August 2008 }}. The Georgian Times. Retrieved on 11 July 2008.</ref>\n\nHis 27 goals scored in the [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup competition]] ranks him 5th in the [[UEFA Europa League|tournament's history]].<ref name=\"arveladzefund1\">[http://www.arveladzefund.com/eng/shoti.htm Shota's Biography] {{in lang|es}}</ref> He has the best strike record [[Football in Georgia|of independent Georgian Football]]. He was nominated as the best player of [[Football in Georgia|Georgia]] as well as the best player by the [[Umaglesi Liga|Georgian Professional Football league]] survey.\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Tbilisi and Trabzonspor===\nArveladze played at [[FC Dinamo Tbilisi|Dinamo Tbilisi]], [[Trabzonspor]], and [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]], and finished at least one season as the top goal scorer at all three. In 1993, he scored an effective first [[UEFA competitions#For clubs|Euro Tournament]] goal in the history of independent [[Football in Georgia|Georgian Football]] in the match against [[Linfield F.C.|Linfield]], [[Northern Ireland]]. When he led [[Trabzonspor]] in goals in [[1995\u201396 1.Lig|1995\u201396]], he also led the [[S\u00fcper Lig]], making him the second non-[[Turkey|Turk]] to date to lead that [[S\u00fcper Lig|league]] in goals after [[Tarik Hod\u017ei\u0107]] [[1983\u201384 1.Lig|1983\u201384]]. He is recorded as ''\"most loved foreign player\"'' for [[Trabzonspor#Support|Trabzonspor supporters]].{{citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\n===Ajax Amsterdam===\nIn summer 1997, Arveladze signed for [[Ajax Amsterdam]].<ref name=\"Shoti1\">{{cite book |last=Arveladze |first=Shota |authorlink=Arveladze |date=2012 |title=Yesterday (My Autobiography) |edition=1st |url=http://www.sportall.ge/fexburti/qarthuli-fekhburthi/skhvadaskhva/34055-fragmentebi-shotha-arveladzis-avtobiografiuli-tsignidan-qgushinq.html |access-date=31 May 2017}}</ref> Later, he declared that he was so nervous during his first training session, that he even forgot to take [[football boot]]s with him.<ref name=\"Shoti1\" /> He became a close friend to [[Ronald de Boer]] during his spell in [[Amsterdam]].<ref name=\"Shoti1\" /> His first game at [[Amsterdam Arena]] was a special day for the Georgian player. On 15 August 1997, [[Ajax Amsterdam]] faced Brazilian side [[Gr\u00eamio Foot-Ball Porto Alegrense|Gr\u00eamio]] in a friendly game. Arveladze scored a goal, while his wife Tamuna gave birth to their first child, Giorgi hours before the game.<ref name=\"Shoti1\" />\n\nArveladze made a debut for Ajax against [[Vitesse Arnhem]], where he replaced [[Gerald Sibon]] and scored the fourth goal for the club.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.worldfootball.net/report/eredivisie-1997-1998-afc-ajax-vitesse/ | title = Ajax 5-0 Vitesse (Match Report) | website = worldfootball.net | date = 19 August 1997 | access-date = 31 May 2017}}</ref> During his first season, he scored three [[hat-trick]]s in [[1997\u201398 Eredivisie|Eredivisie]] and total 25 goals in 31 appearances. The manager of the Amsterdam-based club [[Morten Olsen]] was very pleased with the performance of the young striker.<ref name=\"Shoti2\">{{cite book |last=Arveladze |first=Shota |authorlink=Arveladze |date=2012 |title=Yesterday (My Autobiography) |edition=1st |url=http://www.sportall.ge/fexburti/qarthuli-fekhburthi/skhvadaskhva/34181-fragmentebi-shotha-arveladzis-avtobiografiuli-tsignidan-qgushinq.html |access-date=31 May 2017}}</ref> Arveladze was a key figure for the club during [[1997\u201398 UEFA Cup]] as well. He scored 7 goals in 8 games for the club, including [[hat-trick]] against [[NK Maribor]].<ref name=\"Shoti2\" /> Ajax were eliminated in quarter-finals, against [[FC Spartak Moscow|Spartak Moscow]]. Arveladze scored the club's single goal in a tie.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.worldfootball.net/report/europa-league-1997-1998-viertelfinale-afc-ajax-spartak-moskva/ | title = Ajax 1-3 Spartak Moscow (Match Report) | website = worldfootball.net | date = 3 March 1998 | access-date = 31 May 2017}}</ref> During his first season, he faced twice [[NAC Breda]], where his twin brother [[Archil Arveladze|Archil]] played. This remains as one of the most memorable facts in Shota's career.<ref name=\"Shoti2\" />\n\nIn summer 1998, Ajax signed Arveladze's close friend [[Giorgi Kinkladze]] from [[Manchester City]] for \u00a35 million.<ref name=\"Complete Record\">{{cite book |title=Manchester City \u2013 The Complete Record |first=Gary |last=James |publisher=Breedon Books Publishing |year=2006 |location=Derby |pages=224\u20135 |isbn=1-85983-512-0 }}</ref> They had been friends since their childhood and that looked like a dream move for both.<ref name=\"Shoti2\" /> However, Kinkladze's spell at Ajax proved unsuccessful.<ref name=\"Ajax_agony\">{{cite news |title=Kinky: Jim saved me from Ajax agony |first=Dave |last=Smith |newspaper=[[The Sunday Mirror]] |date=5 December 1999}}</ref>\n\n===Rangers===\nArveladze joined [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] from [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]] for \u00a33m in 2001.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/r/rangers/1515958.stm | title = Arveladze ready for Ibrox fight | website = BBC.co.uk | date = 29 August 2001 | access-date = 19 April 2017}}</ref> He agreed a four-year deal with the club. It was obvious that the Georgian would face a fierce competitions for the starting place in the Rangers' strikeforce from the players like [[Tore Andre Flo]], [[Claudio Caniggia]], [[Michael Mols]], [[Kenny Miller]], [[Billy Dodds]], [[Ronald de Boer]] and [[Russell Latapy]].\n\nDuring the first season with [[Glasgow]]-based club, Arveladze scored 17 goals overall, including 11 in [[2001\u201302 Scottish Premier League|Scottish Premier League]]. He only managed to take part in 30 games, after being injured in February in the quarterfinal of the [[2001\u201302 Scottish Cup|Scottish Cup]] against [[Forfar Athletic F.C.|Forfar Athletic]],<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=18343.html | title = Arveladze out with ankle injury | website = UEFA.com | date = 28 February 2002 | access-date = 2 May 2017}}</ref> an injury which meant he missed the [[2002 Scottish League Cup Final]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espnfc.com/scotland/news/2002/0318/20020318rfcslaurels.html |title=Rangers cannot afford to rest on their laurels |publisher=ESPN |date=18 March 2002 |accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref> However, he scored six goals for his club, which managed to win the [[2002 Scottish Cup Final|title]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/3027153/Scottish-Cup-Final-Celtic-undone-by-Lovenkrands.html | title = Scottish Cup Final: Celtic undone by Lovenkrands | website = The Telegraph | date = 5 May 2002 | access-date = 2 May 2017}}</ref> Arveladze played in the [[2002 Scottish Cup Final|final]], replacing [[Claudio Caniggia]]. This was his first title with the Scottish club.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.theguardian.com/football/2002/may/05/newsstory.sport4 | title = Lovenkrands gets just reward with last-minute winner | website = The Guardian | date = 5 May 2002 | access-date = 2 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe following season was the most successful in the career of the Georgian player. Rangers won treble. In March 2003, Rangers defeated their arch-rivals [[Celtic FC|Celtic]] in [[2003 Scottish League Cup Final|League Cup Final]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/2398103/CIS-Cup-Final-Hartson-makes-Rangers-day.html | title = CIS Cup Final: Hartson makes Rangers' day | website = The Telegraph | date = 17 March 2003 | access-date = 2 May 2017}}</ref> Later in [[2003 Scottish Cup Final|Scottish Cup Final]], Rangers won another title, after they managed to defeat [[Dundee F.C.|Dundee]] with a goal from [[Lorenzo Amoruso]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2405119/Scottish-Cup-Final-Amoruso-adds-to-his-worth.html | title = Scottish Cup Final: Amoruso adds to his worth | website = The Telegraph | date = 1 June 2003 | access-date = 2 May 2017}}</ref> Arveladze's two compatriots, [[Georgi Nemsadze]] and [[Zurab Khizanishvili]] also took part in this game. The latter joined Arveladze at Rangers during that summer.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=77579.html | title = Rangers capture Khizanishvili | website = UEFA.com | date = 26 June 2003 | access-date = 2 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2005, Arveladze declared that he will leave the club after the end of the [[2004\u201305 Scottish Premier League|season]], in which he managed to scored 9 goals. He confirmed receiving offers from the various clubs throughout Europe, including the teams from England, Germany, the Netherlands and Turkey.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=300408.html | title = Arveladze's goodbye to Glasgow | website = UEFA.com | date = 6 May 2005 | access-date = 2 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring his time at Rangers, Arveladze had a nickname ''[[Mr. Bean]]'', because of his facial likeness to [[Rowan Atkinson]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.theguardian.com/football/2004/nov/11/newsstory.sport5 | title = Arveladze ends Old Firm agony for Rangers | website = The Guardian | date = 11 November 2004 | access-date = 2 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring a legal case in 2015, Arveladze's agent claimed that the true transfer fee had been 12 million Euro, the equivalent of \u00a38.5 million at the time.<ref>{{ Cite news | url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/football/former-rangers-strikers-agent-claims-club-paid-four-times-publicised-fee.126003045 |first=Mark |last=Walker | title=Former Rangers striker's agent claims club paid four times publicised fee| publisher=Herald & Times Group |work=The Herald | date=13 May 2015}}</ref> Arveladze scored the 300th goal in the [[Scottish Premier League|SPL]] and was part of Rangers squads that won the domestic treble in [[2002\u201303 in Scottish football|2002\u201303]] and a double in [[2004\u201305 in Scottish football|2004\u201305]].\n\n===AZ===\nArveladze departed Rangers for Dutch side [[AZ (football club)|AZ]] on a [[Free transfer (association football)|free transfer]] before the start of [[2005\u201306 Eredivisie|2005\u201306]] season, signing a two-year deal with the club.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://spfl.co.uk/news/article/arveladze-joins-alkmaar-2005-06-08/ | title = Arveladze Joins Alkmaar | website = SPFL.com | date = 8 June 2005 | access-date = 2 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=307884.html | title = Alkmaar secure Arveladze's services | website = UEFA.com | date = 7 June 2005 | access-date = 19 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nUnder the guidance of [[Louis van Gaal]], Arveladze became the key figure of the club.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=343184.html | title = Alkmaar enjoy the high life | website = UEFA.com | date = 23 September 2005 | access-date = 19 April 2017}}</ref> He scored 22 goals in [[2005\u201306 Eredivisie|Eredivisie]], becoming the second best top-scorer of the tournament after [[Klaas-Jan Huntelaar]], who scored 33 goals during the season. Alkmaar participated in [[2005\u201306 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]] this time as well. In 6 game for the club, Arveladze made 2 assists and scored 2 goals, one of them against [[Real Betis]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2005/matches/round=2210/match=82452/index.html | title = Alkmaar - Real Betis (Match Report) | website = UEFA.com | date = 23 February 2006 | access-date = 2 April 2017}}</ref> At the end of the season, AZ Alkmaar and Arveladze agreed a contract extension to keep the Georgian international striker at the Dutch club until the summer of 2008.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=441907.html | title = Arveladze committed to AZ cause | website = UEFA.com | date = 3 August 2006 | access-date = 2 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring the second and the final season with the club, Arveladze was appointed as the new captain of the club.<ref name=\"SHOTA1\" >{{cite web | url = http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=484652.html | title = Forward march for Arveladze | website = UEFA.com | date = 29 November 2006 | access-date = 19 April 2017}}</ref> He was offered the armband after [[Denny Landzaat]] and [[Joris Mathijsen]] left for [[Wigan Athletic FC|Wigan Athletic]] and [[Hamburger SV]] respectively.<ref name=\"SHOTA1\" /> The Georgian was praised by [[Louis van Gaal]], under whose guidance he played at [[Ajax Amsterdam]] as well. Van Gaal compared Arveladze to [[Danny Blind]] and [[Frank Rijkaard]] in terms of personality, calling him ''the top professional in the squad''.<ref name=\"SHOTA1\" />\n\nHe scored 23 goals, accumulating total 48 goals for AZ in 89 competitive appearances. The Georgian striker scored 7 goals in [[2006\u201307 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]] as well, two of them in [[Ram\u00f3n S\u00e1nchez Pizju\u00e1n Stadium]] in a 2\u20131 away win against [[FC Sevilla|Sevilla]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=469248.html | title = Arveladze steals Sevilla's thunder | website = UEFA.com | date = 15 December 2006 | access-date = 19 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Levante===\nIn July 2007, Arveladze passed a medical and agreed a one-year contract with the Spanish club [[Levante UD|Levante]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=560700.html | title = Arveladze accepts Levante chance | website = UEFA.com | date = 12 July 2007 | access-date = 2 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nUnfortunately he injured during the summer training session of the club and missed nearly ten months.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://archivo.marca.com/edicion/marca/futbol/1a_division/levante/es/desarrollo/1103977.html | title = Arveladze: \"Me volv\u00ed a sentir futbolista\" | website = Marca.com | date = 25 March 2008 | access-date = 18 April 2017}}</ref> He got injured in July and when underwent surgery in [[Amsterdam]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=565796.html | title = Amsterdam trip for injured Arveladze | website = UEFA.com | date = 30 July 2007 | access-date = 2 April 2017}}</ref> The Georgian returned and made a debut against [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]] in March, replacing [[Juanma (footballer, born 1981)|Juanma]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/p.php?id=25084 | title = Levante - Villarreal (Match Report) | website = BDFutbol.com | date = 23 March 2008 | access-date = 18 April 2017}}</ref> He managed to take part in other 3 games until the end of the [[2007-08 La Liga|season]].\n\nIn April, Levante confirmed that Arveladze would retire at the end of the season.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.espnfc.com/story/524984/levante-arveladze-se-retirara-en-mayo | title = Levante: Arveladze se retirar\u00e1 en mayo | website = ESPN.com | date = 11 April 2008 | access-date = 18 April 2017}}</ref> In the last game of his career he played at [[Santiago Bernab\u00e9u Stadium|Santiago Bernabeu]] against [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]], in which ''Los Blancos'' won 5-2.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/p.php?id=25177 | title = Real Madrid - Levante (Match Report) | website = BDFutbol.com | date = 18 May 2008 | access-date = 18 April 2017}}</ref> He replaced [[Laurent Courtois]].\n\n==International career==\nShota Arveladze was a regular in the [[Georgia national football team|Georgian national team]]<ref name=\"levanteud1\">[http://www.levanteud.com/noticias/levante6716.html Arveladze bids farewell to the national team of Georgia] {{in lang|es}}</ref> and is its all-time leading scorer with 26 goals in his 61 games.<ref name=\"Bibileishvili\"/> With Georgia he won in 1998 the [[Malta International Football Tournament]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://eu-football.info/_match.php?id=11048 | title = Georgia vs Latvia international football match report | website = eu-football.info | date = 6 February 1998 | access-date = 16 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nAfter retiring as a player, Arveladze was appointed as [[Assistant coach|assistant manager]] of [[AZ (football club)|AZ]] under head coach and former [[AFC Ajax#List of Ajax managers|Ajax coach]] [[Louis van Gaal]] in July 2008. He maintained this position in the [[2009\u201310 Eredivisie|2009\u201310 season]] under [[Ronald Koeman]] and [[Dick Advocaat]]. \n\nFor the [[2010\u201311 in Turkish football|2010\u201311 season]], Arveladze served as [[Manager (association football)|manager]] of [[List of football clubs in Turkey|Turkish side]] [[Kayserispor]].<ref name=\"autogeneratedvi\">{{cite news |url=http://www.vi.nl/Nieuws-item/179928/Arveladze-gaat-als-trainer-aan-de-slag-bij-Kayserispor.htm |publisher=Voetbal International |accessdate=5 May 2010 |date=5 May 2010 |language=Dutch |title=Arveladze gaat als trainer aan de slag bij Kayserispor }}</ref><ref name=\"kayserispor1\">{{cite news |url=http://www.kayserispor.org/kayserispor-transfer-2010-2011-dosyasi.html|publisher=Kayserispor |accessdate=5 May 2010 |date=4 May 2010 |language=Turkish|title=Kayserispor Transfer 2010-2011 Dosyas\u0131 }}</ref>\n\nFrom 2012 to 2015, Arveladze managed Istanbul-based [[Kas\u0131mpa\u015fa SK]].\n\nOn 3 July 2015, Arveladze was named manager of Turkish side [[Trabzonspor]]. Arveladze resigned on November 2015 after back to back poor results with the team.\n\nIn June 2016 Arveladze was announced as the new head coach of Israeli club [[Maccabi Tel Aviv F.C.]] Around the middle of the season, Arveladze was fired due to series of poor results on his side.\n\n==Personal life==\nArveladze played football on a high level well into his thirties despite having to deal with chronic asthma his entire career.\n\nHis brothers [[Archil Arveladze|Archil]] and [[Revaz Arveladze|Revaz]] also played International football. His son [[Giorgi Arveladze (footballer)|Giorgi Arveladze]] is also a footballer.{{citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Club===\n:Sources:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mackolik.com/Futbolcu/6858/Shota-Arveladze|title=Shota Arveladze Career statistics|publisher=mackolik.com|date=22 June 2012|accessdate=22 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"nft\">{{NFT|2518|name=Shota Arveladze |accessdate=22 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup{{efn|Includes [[Georgian Cup]], [[Turkish Cup]], [[KNVB Cup]], [[Scottish Cup]], [[Scottish League Cup]] and [[Copa del Rey]]}}\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[UEFA#Club|Europe]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"6\"|[[FC Dinamo Tbilisi|Dinamo Tbilisi]]\n|[[1991 Umaglesi Liga|1990\u201391]]\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[Umaglesi Liga]]\n|7||3||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||7||3\n|-\n|[[1991\u201392 Umaglesi Liga|1991\u201392]]\n|30||22||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||30||22\n|-\n|[[1992\u201393 Umaglesi Liga|1992\u201393]]\n|23||18||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||23||18\n|-\n|[[1993\u201394 Umaglesi Liga|1993\u201394]]\n|7||8||0||0||2||1||9||9\n|-\n|[[1994-95 Umaglesi Liga|1994\u201395]]\n|8||11||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||8||11\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!75!!62!!0!!0!!2!!1!!77!!63\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[Trabzonspor]]\n|[[1993\u201394 1.Lig|1993\u201394]]\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[S\u00fcper Lig]]\n|18||15||4||4||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||22||19\n|-\n|[[1994\u201395 1.Lig|1994\u201395]]\n|17||12||6||6||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||23||18\n|-\n|[[1995\u201396 1.Lig|1995\u201396]]\n|34||25||3||2||4||1||41||28\n|-\n|[[1996\u201397 1.Lig|1996\u201397]]\n|27||9||6||3||4||4||37||16\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!96!!61!!19!!15!!8!!5!!123!!81\n|-\n|rowspan=\"6\"|[[AFC Ajax|Ajax]]\n|[[1997\u201398 Eredivisie|1997\u201398]]\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[Eredivisie]]\n|31||25||5||5||8||7||44||37\n|-\n|[[1998\u201399 Eredivisie|1998\u201399]]\n|19||7||3||1||3||0||25||8\n|-\n|[[1999\u20132000 Eredivisie|1999\u20132000]]\n|17||5||1||0||2||1||20||6\n|-\n|[[2000\u201301 Eredivisie|2000\u201301]]\n|27||18||1||0||3||2||31||20\n|-\n|[[2001\u201302 Eredivisie|2001\u201302]]\n|2||0||0||0||2||1||4||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!96!!55!!10!!6!!18!!11!!124!!72\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]\n|[[2001\u201302 Scottish Premier League|2001\u201302]]\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Scottish Premier League]]\n|22||11||8||6||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||30||17\n|-\n|[[2002\u201303 Scottish Premier League|2002\u201303]]\n|30||15||8||1||2||0||40||16\n|-\n|[[2003\u201304 Scottish Premier League|2003\u201304]]\n|19||12||4||2||6||1||29||15\n|-\n|[[2004\u201305 Scottish Premier League|2004\u201305]]\n|24||6||2||1||7||2||33||9\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!95!!44!!22!!10!!15!!3!!132!!57\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[AZ (football club)|AZ]]\n|[[2005\u201306 Eredivisie|2005\u201306]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Eredivisie\n|31||22||5||1||6||2||42||25\n|-\n|[[2006\u201307 Eredivisie|2006\u201307]]\n|29||14||7||2||11||7||47||23\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!60!!36!!12!!3!!17!!9!!89!!48\n|-\n|[[Levante UD|Levante]]\n|[[2007\u201308 La Liga|2007\u201308]]\n|[[La Liga]]\n|4||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||4||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!426!!258!!63!!34!!60!!29!!549!!321\n|}\n\n{{notelist}}\n\n===International===\n:Source:<ref name=\"nft\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|colspan=\"3\"|[[Georgia national football team|Georgia national team]]\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|1992||2||1\n|-\n|1994||6||3\n|-\n|1995||6||2\n|-\n|1996||5||0\n|-\n|1997||6||5\n|-\n|1998||5||0\n|-\n|1999||3||3\n|-\n|2000||3||0\n|-\n|2001||6||1\n|-\n|2002||2||1\n|-\n|2003||4||3\n|-\n|2004||4||0\n|-\n|2005||3||1\n|-\n|2006||5||5\n|-\n|2007||1||1\n|-\n!Total||61||26\n|}\n\n===International goals===\n:Source:<ref name=\"nft\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! # !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n| 1. || 17 September 1992 || David Kipiani Stadium, [[Gurjaani]] || {{fb|AZE}} || '''4'''\u20131 || 6\u20133 || [[Exhibition game|Friendly]]\n|-\n| 2. || 19 July 1992 || [[Boris Paichadze Stadium]], [[Tbilisi]] || {{fb|Malta}} || '''1'''\u20131 || 1\u20131 || Friendly